/wiki/General_Leonidas_Plaza_Guti%C3%A9r: Leónidas Plaza y Gutiérrez de Caviedes (April 18, 1865 – November 17, 1932) was an Ecuadorian politician who was the president of Ecuador for two separate occasions, from September 1, 1901 to August 31, 1905 and again from September 1, 1912 to August 31, 1916.
/wiki/Logro%C3%B1o_Canton: Logroño Canton is a canton of Ecuador, located in the Morona-Santiago Province.  Its capital is the town of Logroño.  Its population at the 2001 census was 4,621. The current town of Logroño is in the vicinity of the lost 16th century mining town of Logroño de los Caballeros.
/wiki/Logro%C3%B1o,_Ecuador: Logroño is a town in Morona-Santiago Province, Ecuador. It is the seat of Logroño Canton. It has a population of 5,723, the majority of which are Shuar. There is a network of limestone caves 2 km from the town, "Caverna de Las Cascadas".
/wiki/Morona_Canton: Morona Canton is a canton of Ecuador, located in the Morona-Santiago Province.  Its capital is the town of Morona.  Its population at the 2001 census was 5,065.
/wiki/Macas_(city): Macas (Spanish pronunciation: [ˈmakas]) is the capital of Morona Santiago province in southeastern Ecuador. The city is also the seat of the county Morona. Known as the "Emerald of the East" due to its location east of the Andes mountains, Macas lies in the Upano Valley overlooking the Upano river. The city has a population of 14,054 inhabitants and along with Tena and Puyo served under Spanish rule as one of Ecuador's main staging points for the colonization of the Amazon and the subjugation of its indigenous peoples.  Beginning in the 1960s indigenous people have organized political federations and movements, and often locate the seats of their organizations in such cities and use them as central places for regional congresses.  Macas has also been promoting tourism.
